President Biden delivered a speech in the South Court Auditorium of the Eisenhower Executive Office Building, thanking labor leaders and lawmakers for their support in protecting workers' pensions. He emphasized the importance of unions and the middle class in building America and acknowledged the challenges faced by the middle class in recent years. Biden highlighted the American Rescue Plan, which included the Butch Lewis Act to secure pension plans for union workers. He announced that $36 billion of the plan's funds will be used to prevent drastic cuts to workers' pension benefits. Biden emphasized the impact of these cuts on the dignity and financial security of workers and their families. He praised the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation for their work in implementing the program. The President concluded by reaffirming his commitment to rebuilding the middle class and creating an economy that benefits all Americans.